<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="8176">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="8176">
<taxonomicName class="Eurotiomycetes" family="Verrucariaceae" genus="Heteroplacidium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Heteroplacidium compactum" order="Verrucariales" pageId="0" pageNumber="8176" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="compactum">Heteroplacidium compactum</taxonomicName>
is widely distributed worldwide. It was previously reported from Utah as 
<taxonomicName class="Eurotiomycetes" family="Verrucariaceae" genus="Catapyrenium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Catapyrenium compactum" order="Verrucariales" pageId="0" pageNumber="8176" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="compactum">Catapyrenium compactum</taxonomicName>
(A. Massal.) R. Sant. by 
<bibRefCitation author="St. Clair, L. L." journalOrPublisher="Mycotaxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="8176" pagination="199 - 264" title="Catalog of the lichens of Utah" volume="40" year="1991">St. Clair et al. (1991)</bibRefCitation>
. This lichen begins as a parasite on other lichens, and then grows independently. Fig. 20 shows our specimen growing partly scattered among and likely parasitic on 
<taxonomicName class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Teloschistaceae" genus="Caloplaca" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Caloplaca trachyphylla" order="Teloschistales" pageId="0" pageNumber="8176" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="trachyphylla">Caloplaca trachyphylla</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
